    "preparations_description": "The main herbal preparations of Tepualia stipularis are infusion, tincture, tea, decoction, and salve. Infusion involves steeping the leaves in hot water to extract the bioactive compounds, while tincture is a concentrated liquid extract made with ethanol or glycerin. Tea is prepared by infusing the leaves in hot water for a shorter period than infusion, resulting in a milder flavor and aroma. Decoction is a method used for harder plant parts like roots and bark, involving boiling them in water to extract the desired compounds, but Tepualia stipularis is typically prepared as a leaf infusion or tea. Salve is a topical preparation made by infusing the leaves in a carrier oil, allowing the bioactive compounds to be absorbed through the skin for local therapeutic effects.",
