    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Tepualia stipularis improperly include inducing nausea, which is caused by the plant's toxic compounds, and causing diarrhea due to its irritant properties. Experiencing nausea is a common symptom of incorrect usage, as the body reacts to the presence of toxic substances. In severe cases, improper use can lead to respiratory failure, a potentially life-threatening condition. This is because the plant's toxic compounds can disrupt normal respiratory function, leading to a build-up of carbon dioxide in the blood and a decrease in oxygen levels. The severity of these side effects increases with the amount and duration of improper use, making it essential to handle Tepualia stipularis with caution.",
    "uses": "Tepualia stipularis is a plant species native to the Andes, but information on its medicinal uses is limited. Tepualia stipularis has been used in traditional medicine in some regions, but its effectiveness and safety have not been extensively scientifically studied. It's often used to treat various health issues, including fever, rheumatism, and digestive problems. However, more research is needed to confirm its efficacy and potential side effects. Traditional healers continue to use Tepualia stipularis in their practices, but caution is advised when using it for medicinal purposes.",
    "taxonomy": "Tepualia stipularis is a species of flowering plant in the family Myrtaceae. It is native to South America and is closely related to other plants in the same family. The Myrtaceae family includes a wide range of plants such as eucalyptus, guava, and clove. This family is commonly known as the myrtle family. The classification of Tepualia stipularis places it within the broader context of the flowering plant kingdom.",
    "benefits": "Tepualia stipularis is known for its potential medicinal properties, with studies suggesting its extracts may have antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, and antimicrobial effects. These properties could contribute to the plant's traditional uses in treating various health conditions, including infections and wounds. Furthermore, Tepualia stipularis may also have antiviral and antifungal activities, which could be beneficial in the prevention and treatment of diseases. However, more research is needed to fully understand the plant's health benefits and potential applications. The extracts of Tepualia stipularis may also have anti-cancer properties, although this requires further investigation.",
    "parts": "I found that Tepualia stipularis, a plant native to South America, is used in traditional medicine for its medicinal properties. The plant's bark and roots are used in various medicinal preparations.  However, further information on the specific medicinal parts used is limited. More research is needed to confirm the effectiveness and safety of using Tepualia stipularis in medicine. The traditional uses of the plant should be verified by a qualified healthcare professional.",
    "intro": "Tepualia stipularis, also known as the Guanabara tea tree or simply Guayap\u00e9, is a species of flowering plant in the family Cunoniaceae, native to the subtropical regions of South America. The plant is valued for its potential health benefits, including antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, and antimicrobial properties, which may help to protect against oxidative stress, reduce inflammation, and prevent infections. The bioactive constituents of Tepualia stipularis include flavonoids, phenolic acids, and other polyphenolic compounds, which are responsible for its medicinal properties. Guayap\u00e9 is commonly used to make herbal teas, infusions, and extracts, which are often consumed for their potential health benefits, although more research is needed to confirm its efficacy and safety."
